article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw, the leading scorer and rebounder in the WNBA, suffered a high ankle sprain with 7:19 to play in the first half of the Fire's 72-66 win over the Mystics on an injury-filled Friday night.
article.headline: Holdsclaw's injury 'looks like it's not too serious'
article.linkText: Holdsclaw injured as Mystics lose battle of attrition to Fire
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw was on crutches in the
Washington Mystics' lockerroom. Over on the Portland side, DeMya
Walker was with a dentist and Jackie Stiles was hobbling around in
a walking cast.

Holdsclaw, the leading scorer and rebounder in the WNBA, suffered a high ankle sprain with 7:19 to play in the first half of the Fire's 72-66 win over the Mystics on an injury-filled Friday night.

"It looks like it's not too serious,'' Mystics coach Marianne
Stanley said of Holdsclaw's injury. "Right now I really don't know
what the status is, so we'll probably have it re-X-rayed.''

Walker left the game with a minute remaining when her face collided with the knee of Washington's Murriel Page. Walker had to be helped off the court and was bleeding profusely from the mouth.

"It's not good right now,'' Fire coach Linda Hargrove said. "She's with the dentist right now, and we don't have a final answer. It was a pretty violent hit.''

Stiles, last season's WNBA rookie of the year, faces possible season-ending surgery because of bursitis in her right heel, an injury that started bothering her in training camp. She was placed on the injured list before the game.

Stacey Thomas and Kristin Folkl each scored 12 points as
Portland nearly blew a 20-point lead in the second half.

Ukari Figgs and Sylvia Crawley each had 11 points for the Fire
(6-8), who beat the top two Eastern Conference teams in consecutive
games. Portland defeated second-place Orlando on Wednesday.

Coco Miller led the Mystics (10-4) with 17 points. Stacey
Dales-Schuman added 14 points and six assists.

Holdsclaw was fighting for a loose ball underneath the
Washington basket with Walker when she was hurt. Her left leg was
pinned under Walker, and replays showed her ankle buckle and her
knee twist at an awkward angle.

Trainers for the Mystics examined both the ankle and knee along the baseline out of bounds while play resumed.

Holdsclaw had three points and two rebounds and the Mystics trailed 20-18 when she left. The Fire scored the next 12 points to take control of the game going into halftime.

The Fire led by 20 in the second half, but Washington climbed
back in with an extended run late in the game.

"I don't think we were mentally ready to play against an aggressive defense today,'' Stanley said. "I'm not sure exactly why we weren't but it was disappointing to see. We didn't handle the defense that they threw at us very well.

"If you spot anybody in this league a 20-point lead, they ought
to be able to hang on to it.''

Thomas hit a key 3-pointer with 2:44 remaining to end the run,
and Portland was able to hold on.

Stiles has already missed four games this season due to the
injury. Since returning to action June 15, Stiles has not played
more than 19 minutes in a game and has been a reserve for the first
time in her playing career.

"She's not satisfied with the level where she's played at,'' Hargrove said. "She wants to be back where she was. Hopefully with this time off we'll be able to get her well.''

Offseason surgery on her right wrist has also limited her
effectiveness. This year Stiles is averaging just 6.0 points a game
and shooting 23.1 percent, compared to her totals of 14.9 points
and 40.5 percent from last year.

If the heel does not respond to rest and rehabilitation, surgery is a strong possibility. Recovery time is eight weeks, which would keep her out the rest of the season.

Portland activated forward Carolyn Young from the injured listto replace Stiles.
